ere the Manuel des péchés (commonly known through its English translation Handlyng Synne), The Speculum Vitae, and Chaucer's Parson's Tale. This book is the first full-length overview of this body of writing and its material and social contexts. It shows that while manuals for penitents developed under the Church's control, they also became a site of the Church's concern. Manuals such as the Compileison (which was addressed to a much broader audience than its English analogue, Ancrene Wisse) brought learning that had been controlled by the Church into the hands of layfolk and, in so doing, raised significant concerns over who should have access to knowledge. Clerics worried that these manuals might accidentally teach people new sins, remind them of old ones, or become sites of prurient interest. This finding, and others explored in this book, call for a new awareness of the complications and contradictions inherent in late medieval orthodoxy and reveal plainly that even writing that happened firmly within the Church's control could promote new and complex ways of thinking about religion and the self.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismyMiddle English, 1100-1500. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aPenancexHistoryzEnglandyTo 1500. 0aPenitentialsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPenitents in art. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAncrene Wisse.  aChurch control.  aManuals for Penitents.  aMedieval England.  aParson's Tale.  aconfession.  aknowledge dissemination.  alayfolk.  amedieval culture.  amedieval texts.  amorality.  aorthodoxy.  areligious literature.  asin.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttp